</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Orthotopic liver transplantation is becoming an increasingly routine procedure for a variety of benign and malignant diseases of the liver and biliary system. Continued improvements in surgical techniques and post-transplantation immunosuppression regimens have resulted in better graft and patient survival. A number of potentially treatable nonvascular complications of liver transplantation are visible at imaging, and accurate diagnosis of these complications allows patients to benefit from potential treatment options. Biliary complications include stricture (anastomotic and nonanastomotic), leak, biloma formation, and development of intraductal stones. Pathologic conditions, including hepatitis C infection, hepatocellular carcinoma, hepatic steatosis, and primary sclerosing cholangitis, may recur after liver transplantation. Transplant patients are at increased risk for developing de novo malignancy, including post-transplantation lymphoproliferative disorder, which results from immunosuppression. Patients are also at increased risk for systemic infection from immunosuppression, and patients with hepatic artery and biliary complications are at increased risk for liver abscess. Transplant recipients are typically followed with serial liver function testing; abnormal serum liver function test results may be the first indication that there is a problem with the transplanted liver. Ultrasonography is typically the first imaging test performed to try to identify the cause of abnormal liver function test results. Computed tomography, magnetic resonance imaging, angiography, and/or cholangiography may be necessary for further evaluation. Accurately diagnosing nonvascular complications of liver transplantation that are visible at imaging is critically important for patients to benefit from appropriate treatment.</div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2015</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.351130023">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.351130023">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130023/asset/images/large/rg.351130023.fig1.jpeg" height="2300" width="3800" aria-labelledby="fig1" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1</span> Available surgical techniques for liver transplantation. <i>A,</i> Illustration shows the conventional technique, in which five standard anastomoses are performed: end-to-end hepatic artery anastomosis, end-to-end portal vein anastomosis, two end-to-end <abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr> anastomoses (supra- and infrahepatic), and end-to-end choledochocholedochostomy. <i>B,</i> Illustration shows the recently developed piggyback technique, a modification of the conventional technique, in which the <abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr> anastomoses are replaced by a single anastomosis of the donor suprahepatic <abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr> to the confluence of the recipient’s right and main hepatic veins, with the recipient’s native retrohepatic <abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr> remaining in situ. <i>C,</i> Illustration shows the living-donor right lobe transplantation technique, in which conventional right hepatectomy is followed by anastomoses of the donor right hepatic vein <i>(RHV)</i> and the recipient hepatic artery <i>(HA)</i> (end-to-end), the donor right portal vein <i>(RPV)</i> and the recipient portal vein <i>(PV)</i> (end-to-end), the donor <i>RHV</i> and main hepatic vein <i>(MHV)</i> and the recipient retrohepatic <abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr> (end-to-side) or hepatic vein confluence (end-to-end), and the donor right hepatic duct and the recipient jejunal limb with Roux-en-Y reconstruction. <i>D,</i> Illustration shows the split-liver technique, which involves dividing the donor liver into segments II and III, which are given to a pediatric recipient with the following anastomoses: the donor left hepatic artery <i>(LHA)</i> to the recipient hepatic artery <i>(HA)</i> (end-to-end), the donor left portal vein <i>(LPV)</i> to the recipient portal vein <i>(PV)</i> (end-to-end), the donor left hepatic vein <i>(LHV)</i> to the recipient retrohepatic <abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr> (end-to-side), and a Roux-en-Y biliary reconstruction to the donor left hepatic duct <i>(LHD)</i>. The remaining liver is transplanted into an adult with the same anastomoses as those used in the living donor right lobe transplantation technique, except the biliary anastomosis is a choledochocholedochostomy. <i>E,</i> Illustration shows the living-donor left lobe technique, which is performed with the same anastomoses as those used in the pediatric split-liver technique, although sometimes segment IV is included in the donor liver. (Courtesy of Eric Jablonowski, Media and Communications Services, Emory University School of Medicine.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130023&amp;id=fig1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130023/asset/images/large/rg.351130023.fig2.jpeg" height="1738" width="2500" aria-labelledby="fig2" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2</span> Flowchart shows the different imaging categories and patterns of nonvascular complications after <abbr title="orthotopic liver transplantation">OLT</abbr>. <i>HCC</i> = hepatocellular cancer, <i>PSC</i> = primary sclerosing cholangitis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130023&amp;id=fig2">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130023/asset/images/large/rg.351130023.fig3a.jpeg" height="766" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig3a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span> Anastomotic stricture. <b>(a)</b> CT cholangiogram shows an anastomotic stricture (arrow) at the choledochojejunostomy site, with secondary mild intrahepatic ductal dilatation. <b>(b)</b> Percutaneous cholangiogram shows multiple round intraductal filling defects (arrow), a finding compatible with stones. <b>(c)</b> Percutaneous cholangiogram obtained after cholangioplasty shows multiple stones within the jejunum (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130023&amp;id=fig3a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130023/asset/images/large/rg.351130023.fig3b.jpeg" height="654" width="843" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span> Anastomotic stricture. <b>(a)</b> CT cholangiogram shows an anastomotic stricture (arrow) at the choledochojejunostomy site, with secondary mild intrahepatic ductal dilatation. <b>(b)</b> Percutaneous cholangiogram shows multiple round intraductal filling defects (arrow), a finding compatible with stones. <b>(c)</b> Percutaneous cholangiogram obtained after cholangioplasty shows multiple stones within the jejunum (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130023&amp;id=fig3b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130023/asset/images/large/rg.351130023.fig3c.jpeg" height="654" width="832" aria-labelledby="fig3c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3c</span> Anastomotic stricture. <b>(a)</b> CT cholangiogram shows an anastomotic stricture (arrow) at the choledochojejunostomy site, with secondary mild intrahepatic ductal dilatation. <b>(b)</b> Percutaneous cholangiogram shows multiple round intraductal filling defects (arrow), a finding compatible with stones. <b>(c)</b> Percutaneous cholangiogram obtained after cholangioplasty shows multiple stones within the jejunum (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130023&amp;id=fig3c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130023/asset/images/large/rg.351130023.fig4a.jpeg" height="699" width="808" aria-labelledby="fig4a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span> Anastomotic stricture. <b>(a)</b> Percutaneous transhepatic cholangiogram shows focal narrowing at the choledochojejunostomy site (arrow) and suprastenotic dilatation. <b>(b)</b> Maximum intensity projection (MIP) image from <abbr title="MR cholangiopancreatography">MRCP</abbr> shows an anastomotic stricture (arrow) and severe suprastenotic dilatation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130023&amp;id=fig4a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130023/asset/images/large/rg.351130023.fig4b.jpeg" height="699" width="767" aria-labelledby="fig4b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span> Anastomotic stricture. <b>(a)</b> Percutaneous transhepatic cholangiogram shows focal narrowing at the choledochojejunostomy site (arrow) and suprastenotic dilatation. <b>(b)</b> Maximum intensity projection (MIP) image from <abbr title="MR cholangiopancreatography">MRCP</abbr> shows an anastomotic stricture (arrow) and severe suprastenotic dilatation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130023&amp;id=fig4b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130023/asset/images/large/rg.351130023.fig5a.jpeg" height="698" width="795" aria-labelledby="fig5a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span> Donor-recipient size mismatch. <b>(a)</b> <abbr title="MR cholangiopancreatography">MRCP</abbr> image obtained to evaluate elevated liver function test results shows moderate intra- and extrahepatic biliary ductal dilatation (white arrow) upstream from the anastomosis site and a narrower common bile duct (black arrow) downstream from the anastomosis site. Findings were interpreted as an anastomotic stricture. <b>(b)</b> Follow-up endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatographic (<abbr title="endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography">ERCP</abbr>) image shows a donor bile duct with a diameter of 8 mm (white arrow) and recipient bile duct with a diameter of 5 mm (black arrow) with no focal stenosis, a finding in keeping with a donor-recipient size mismatch. The patient underwent liver biopsy, and abnormal liver function test results were attributed to medication-induced injury.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130023&amp;id=fig5a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130023/asset/images/large/rg.351130023.fig5b.jpeg" height="695" width="780" aria-labelledby="fig5b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span> Donor-recipient size mismatch. <b>(a)</b> <abbr title="MR cholangiopancreatography">MRCP</abbr> image obtained to evaluate elevated liver function test results shows moderate intra- and extrahepatic biliary ductal dilatation (white arrow) upstream from the anastomosis site and a narrower common bile duct (black arrow) downstream from the anastomosis site. Findings were interpreted as an anastomotic stricture. <b>(b)</b> Follow-up endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatographic (<abbr title="endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography">ERCP</abbr>) image shows a donor bile duct with a diameter of 8 mm (white arrow) and recipient bile duct with a diameter of 5 mm (black arrow) with no focal stenosis, a finding in keeping with a donor-recipient size mismatch. The patient underwent liver biopsy, and abnormal liver function test results were attributed to medication-induced injury.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130023&amp;id=fig5b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130023/asset/images/large/rg.351130023.fig6a.jpeg" height="684" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span> Clinically insignificant narrowing. <b>(a)</b> MIP image from <abbr title="MR cholangiopancreatography">MRCP</abbr> obtained 1 month after transplantation as part of an MR imaging study to screen for hepatoma shows focal narrowing at the biliary anastomosis site (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Thin-section <abbr title="MR cholangiopancreatography">MRCP</abbr> image confirms the presence of short-segment anastomotic narrowing (arrow). However, laboratory values were normal, and the patient was asymptomatic. No further testing or treatment was performed. <b>(c)</b> MIP image from <abbr title="MR cholangiopancreatography">MRCP</abbr> performed 4 years later shows a stable focal anastomotic narrowing (arrow). Because the patient remained asymptomatic with normal laboratory values, this stable anastomotic narrowing was thought to be clinically insignificant.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130023&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130023/asset/images/large/rg.351130023.fig6b.jpeg" height="648" width="781" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span> Clinically insignificant narrowing. <b>(a)</b> MIP image from <abbr title="MR cholangiopancreatography">MRCP</abbr> obtained 1 month after transplantation as part of an MR imaging study to screen for hepatoma shows focal narrowing at the biliary anastomosis site (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Thin-section <abbr title="MR cholangiopancreatography">MRCP</abbr> image confirms the presence of short-segment anastomotic narrowing (arrow). However, laboratory values were normal, and the patient was asymptomatic. No further testing or treatment was performed. <b>(c)</b> MIP image from <abbr title="MR cholangiopancreatography">MRCP</abbr> performed 4 years later shows a stable focal anastomotic narrowing (arrow). Because the patient remained asymptomatic with normal laboratory values, this stable anastomotic narrowing was thought to be clinically insignificant.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130023&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130023/asset/images/large/rg.351130023.fig6c.jpeg" height="648" width="795" aria-labelledby="fig6c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6c</span> Clinically insignificant narrowing. <b>(a)</b> MIP image from <abbr title="MR cholangiopancreatography">MRCP</abbr> obtained 1 month after transplantation as part of an MR imaging study to screen for hepatoma shows focal narrowing at the biliary anastomosis site (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Thin-section <abbr title="MR cholangiopancreatography">MRCP</abbr> image confirms the presence of short-segment anastomotic narrowing (arrow). However, laboratory values were normal, and the patient was asymptomatic. No further testing or treatment was performed. <b>(c)</b> MIP image from <abbr title="MR cholangiopancreatography">MRCP</abbr> performed 4 years later shows a stable focal anastomotic narrowing (arrow). Because the patient remained asymptomatic with normal laboratory values, this stable anastomotic narrowing was thought to be clinically insignificant.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130023&amp;id=fig6c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130023/asset/images/large/rg.351130023.fig7a.jpeg" height="715" width="850" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span> Nonanastomotic strictures and ischemic cholangiopathy. <b>(a)</b> Color Doppler US image obtained to evaluate abnormal liver function test results shows intrahepatic biliary ductal dilatation (arrows). <b>(b)</b> T2-weighted MR image confirms the presence of intrahepatic ductal dilatation (black arrows) and intraductal debris (white arrows). <b>(c)</b> <abbr title="endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography">ERCP</abbr> image shows ductal irregularity and intraluminal filling defects (arrow). The patient’s infrarenal arterial jump graft was occluded.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130023&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130023/asset/images/large/rg.351130023.fig7b.jpeg" height="731" width="899" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span> Nonanastomotic strictures and ischemic cholangiopathy. <b>(a)</b> Color Doppler US image obtained to evaluate abnormal liver function test results shows intrahepatic biliary ductal dilatation (arrows). <b>(b)</b> T2-weighted MR image confirms the presence of intrahepatic ductal dilatation (black arrows) and intraductal debris (white arrows). <b>(c)</b> <abbr title="endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography">ERCP</abbr> image shows ductal irregularity and intraluminal filling defects (arrow). The patient’s infrarenal arterial jump graft was occluded.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130023&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130023/asset/images/large/rg.351130023.fig7c.jpeg" height="731" width="776" aria-labelledby="fig7c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7c</span> Nonanastomotic strictures and ischemic cholangiopathy. <b>(a)</b> Color Doppler US image obtained to evaluate abnormal liver function test results shows intrahepatic biliary ductal dilatation (arrows). <b>(b)</b> T2-weighted MR image confirms the presence of intrahepatic ductal dilatation (black arrows) and intraductal debris (white arrows). <b>(c)</b> <abbr title="endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography">ERCP</abbr> image shows ductal irregularity and intraluminal filling defects (arrow). The patient’s infrarenal arterial jump graft was occluded.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130023&amp;id=fig7c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130023/asset/images/large/rg.351130023.fig8a.jpeg" height="731" width="844" aria-labelledby="fig8a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span> Biliary leak. <b>(a)</b> <abbr title="hepato-iminodiacetic acid">HIDA</abbr> scan shows an accumulation of radiotracer (arrows) in the porta hepatis and surgical drainage catheters, a finding indicative of a bile leak. <b>(b)</b> Percutaneous cholangiogram confirms the presence of an active contrast material leak that originates near the biliary anastomosis site (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130023&amp;id=fig8a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130023/asset/images/large/rg.351130023.fig8b.jpeg" height="731" width="830" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span> Biliary leak. <b>(a)</b> <abbr title="hepato-iminodiacetic acid">HIDA</abbr> scan shows an accumulation of radiotracer (arrows) in the porta hepatis and surgical drainage catheters, a finding indicative of a bile leak. <b>(b)</b> Percutaneous cholangiogram confirms the presence of an active contrast material leak that originates near the biliary anastomosis site (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130023&amp;id=fig8b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130023/asset/images/large/rg.351130023.fig9a.jpeg" height="687" width="869" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span> Hepatic artery stenosis and biloma formation. <b>(a)</b> Angiogram shows the hepatic artery (black arrow), which is 90% stenosed. White arrow = common bile duct stent. <b>(b)</b> Unenhanced CT image obtained 2 months later shows several bilomas (arrows), which formed as a result of biliary ischemia and necrosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130023&amp;id=fig9a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130023/asset/images/large/rg.351130023.fig9b.jpeg" height="687" width="806" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span> Hepatic artery stenosis and biloma formation. <b>(a)</b> Angiogram shows the hepatic artery (black arrow), which is 90% stenosed. White arrow = common bile duct stent. <b>(b)</b> Unenhanced CT image obtained 2 months later shows several bilomas (arrows), which formed as a result of biliary ischemia and necrosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130023&amp;id=fig9b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130023/asset/images/large/rg.351130023.fig10a.jpeg" height="648" width="811" aria-labelledby="fig10a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span> Hepatic infarction and biloma. <b>(a)</b> Unenhanced T1-weighted MR image shows a wedge-shaped area of hypointensity (arrow) in the posterior segment of the right hepatic lobe. <b>(b)</b> T2-weighted MR image shows an area of subtle hyperintensity in the posterior segment of the right hepatic lobe (white arrow), with more focal hyperintensity (black arrow) seen anteriorly. <b>(c)</b> MR image obtained in the delayed phase, 3 minutes after administration of contrast material, shows no enhancement in the posterior segment of the right hepatic lobe (white arrow) and a round nonenhancing area anteriorly (black arrow), findings that reflect parenchymal infarction and biloma, respectively. <b>(d)</b> In-phase MR image shows blooming artifact due to air in the biloma (arrow). The hepatic artery was thrombosed, and the posterior segmental branch of the right portal vein was not visible. Arrowhead in <b>a</b>, <b>c</b>, and <b>d</b> = splenic infarction.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130023&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130023/asset/images/large/rg.351130023.fig10b.jpeg" height="648" width="864" aria-labelledby="fig10b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span> Hepatic infarction and biloma. <b>(a)</b> Unenhanced T1-weighted MR image shows a wedge-shaped area of hypointensity (arrow) in the posterior segment of the right hepatic lobe. <b>(b)</b> T2-weighted MR image shows an area of subtle hyperintensity in the posterior segment of the right hepatic lobe (white arrow), with more focal hyperintensity (black arrow) seen anteriorly. <b>(c)</b> MR image obtained in the delayed phase, 3 minutes after administration of contrast material, shows no enhancement in the posterior segment of the right hepatic lobe (white arrow) and a round nonenhancing area anteriorly (black arrow), findings that reflect parenchymal infarction and biloma, respectively. <b>(d)</b> In-phase MR image shows blooming artifact due to air in the biloma (arrow). The hepatic artery was thrombosed, and the posterior segmental branch of the right portal vein was not visible. Arrowhead in <b>a</b>, <b>c</b>, and <b>d</b> = splenic infarction.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130023&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130023/asset/images/large/rg.351130023.fig10c.jpeg" height="649" width="832" aria-labelledby="fig10c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10c</span> Hepatic infarction and biloma. <b>(a)</b> Unenhanced T1-weighted MR image shows a wedge-shaped area of hypointensity (arrow) in the posterior segment of the right hepatic lobe. <b>(b)</b> T2-weighted MR image shows an area of subtle hyperintensity in the posterior segment of the right hepatic lobe (white arrow), with more focal hyperintensity (black arrow) seen anteriorly. <b>(c)</b> MR image obtained in the delayed phase, 3 minutes after administration of contrast material, shows no enhancement in the posterior segment of the right hepatic lobe (white arrow) and a round nonenhancing area anteriorly (black arrow), findings that reflect parenchymal infarction and biloma, respectively. <b>(d)</b> In-phase MR image shows blooming artifact due to air in the biloma (arrow). The hepatic artery was thrombosed, and the posterior segmental branch of the right portal vein was not visible. Arrowhead in <b>a</b>, <b>c</b>, and <b>d</b> = splenic infarction.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130023&amp;id=fig10c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130023/asset/images/large/rg.351130023.fig10d.jpeg" height="649" width="841" aria-labelledby="fig10d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10d</span> Hepatic infarction and biloma. <b>(a)</b> Unenhanced T1-weighted MR image shows a wedge-shaped area of hypointensity (arrow) in the posterior segment of the right hepatic lobe. <b>(b)</b> T2-weighted MR image shows an area of subtle hyperintensity in the posterior segment of the right hepatic lobe (white arrow), with more focal hyperintensity (black arrow) seen anteriorly. <b>(c)</b> MR image obtained in the delayed phase, 3 minutes after administration of contrast material, shows no enhancement in the posterior segment of the right hepatic lobe (white arrow) and a round nonenhancing area anteriorly (black arrow), findings that reflect parenchymal infarction and biloma, respectively. <b>(d)</b> In-phase MR image shows blooming artifact due to air in the biloma (arrow). The hepatic artery was thrombosed, and the posterior segmental branch of the right portal vein was not visible. Arrowhead in <b>a</b>, <b>c</b>, and <b>d</b> = splenic infarction.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130023&amp;id=fig10d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130023/asset/images/large/rg.351130023.fig11a.jpeg" height="606" width="930" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span> Recurrent hepatocellular cancer after liver transplantation. <b>(a)</b> T2-weighted MR image shows a 3.5-cm hyperintense mass (arrow) in the right hepatic lobe. <b>(b)</b> Contrast-enhanced MR image obtained in the arterial phase shows an avid lesion that demonstrates hyperenhancement (arrow) relative to adjacent normal liver. <b>(c)</b> MR image obtained 3 minutes after administration of contrast material shows washout and a pseudocapsule (arrow), findings compatible with hepatocellular cancer. <b>(d)</b> Arteriogram obtained as part of a chemoembolization procedure shows an area of focal hyperenhancement within the tumor (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130023&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130023/asset/images/large/rg.351130023.fig11b.jpeg" height="606" width="945" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span> Recurrent hepatocellular cancer after liver transplantation. <b>(a)</b> T2-weighted MR image shows a 3.5-cm hyperintense mass (arrow) in the right hepatic lobe. <b>(b)</b> Contrast-enhanced MR image obtained in the arterial phase shows an avid lesion that demonstrates hyperenhancement (arrow) relative to adjacent normal liver. <b>(c)</b> MR image obtained 3 minutes after administration of contrast material shows washout and a pseudocapsule (arrow), findings compatible with hepatocellular cancer. <b>(d)</b> Arteriogram obtained as part of a chemoembolization procedure shows an area of focal hyperenhancement within the tumor (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130023&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130023/asset/images/large/rg.351130023.fig11c.jpeg" height="604" width="940" aria-labelledby="fig11c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11c</span> Recurrent hepatocellular cancer after liver transplantation. <b>(a)</b> T2-weighted MR image shows a 3.5-cm hyperintense mass (arrow) in the right hepatic lobe. <b>(b)</b> Contrast-enhanced MR image obtained in the arterial phase shows an avid lesion that demonstrates hyperenhancement (arrow) relative to adjacent normal liver. <b>(c)</b> MR image obtained 3 minutes after administration of contrast material shows washout and a pseudocapsule (arrow), findings compatible with hepatocellular cancer. <b>(d)</b> Arteriogram obtained as part of a chemoembolization procedure shows an area of focal hyperenhancement within the tumor (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130023&amp;id=fig11c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130023/asset/images/large/rg.351130023.fig11d.jpeg" height="604" width="935" aria-labelledby="fig11d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11d</span> Recurrent hepatocellular cancer after liver transplantation. <b>(a)</b> T2-weighted MR image shows a 3.5-cm hyperintense mass (arrow) in the right hepatic lobe. <b>(b)</b> Contrast-enhanced MR image obtained in the arterial phase shows an avid lesion that demonstrates hyperenhancement (arrow) relative to adjacent normal liver. <b>(c)</b> MR image obtained 3 minutes after administration of contrast material shows washout and a pseudocapsule (arrow), findings compatible with hepatocellular cancer. <b>(d)</b> Arteriogram obtained as part of a chemoembolization procedure shows an area of focal hyperenhancement within the tumor (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130023&amp;id=fig11d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130023/asset/images/large/rg.351130023.fig12a.jpeg" height="611" width="848" aria-labelledby="fig12a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span> Nodal recurrence of hepatocellular cancer. <b>(a)</b> T1-weighted MR image shows hypointense material (white arrow) surrounding the <abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr> (black arrow). <b>(b)</b> T2-weighted MR image shows a hyperintense tumor (white arrow) surrounding the <abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr> (black arrow), which is hypointense. <b>(c)</b> MR image obtained in the arterial phase shows hyperenhancement of the tumor (white arrow). Some contrast material is seen in the <abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr> (black arrow). <b>(d)</b> MR image obtained 3 minutes after administration of contrast material shows washout of contrast material from the tumor (white arrow) and residual contrast material in the <abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr> (black arrow). Findings from tissue obtained with a transjugular approach were compatible with metastatic hepatocellular carcinoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130023&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130023/asset/images/large/rg.351130023.fig12b.jpeg" height="611" width="827" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span> Nodal recurrence of hepatocellular cancer. <b>(a)</b> T1-weighted MR image shows hypointense material (white arrow) surrounding the <abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr> (black arrow). <b>(b)</b> T2-weighted MR image shows a hyperintense tumor (white arrow) surrounding the <abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr> (black arrow), which is hypointense. <b>(c)</b> MR image obtained in the arterial phase shows hyperenhancement of the tumor (white arrow). Some contrast material is seen in the <abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr> (black arrow). <b>(d)</b> MR image obtained 3 minutes after administration of contrast material shows washout of contrast material from the tumor (white arrow) and residual contrast material in the <abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr> (black arrow). Findings from tissue obtained with a transjugular approach were compatible with metastatic hepatocellular carcinoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130023&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130023/asset/images/large/rg.351130023.fig12c.jpeg" height="637" width="832" aria-labelledby="fig12c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12c</span> Nodal recurrence of hepatocellular cancer. <b>(a)</b> T1-weighted MR image shows hypointense material (white arrow) surrounding the <abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr> (black arrow). <b>(b)</b> T2-weighted MR image shows a hyperintense tumor (white arrow) surrounding the <abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr> (black arrow), which is hypointense. <b>(c)</b> MR image obtained in the arterial phase shows hyperenhancement of the tumor (white arrow). Some contrast material is seen in the <abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr> (black arrow). <b>(d)</b> MR image obtained 3 minutes after administration of contrast material shows washout of contrast material from the tumor (white arrow) and residual contrast material in the <abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr> (black arrow). Findings from tissue obtained with a transjugular approach were compatible with metastatic hepatocellular carcinoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130023&amp;id=fig12c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130023/asset/images/large/rg.351130023.fig12d.jpeg" height="637" width="843" aria-labelledby="fig12d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12d</span> Nodal recurrence of hepatocellular cancer. <b>(a)</b> T1-weighted MR image shows hypointense material (white arrow) surrounding the <abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr> (black arrow). <b>(b)</b> T2-weighted MR image shows a hyperintense tumor (white arrow) surrounding the <abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr> (black arrow), which is hypointense. <b>(c)</b> MR image obtained in the arterial phase shows hyperenhancement of the tumor (white arrow). Some contrast material is seen in the <abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr> (black arrow). <b>(d)</b> MR image obtained 3 minutes after administration of contrast material shows washout of contrast material from the tumor (white arrow) and residual contrast material in the <abbr title="inferior vena cava">IVC</abbr> (black arrow). Findings from tissue obtained with a transjugular approach were compatible with metastatic hepatocellular carcinoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130023&amp;id=fig12d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130023/asset/images/large/rg.351130023.fig13a.jpeg" height="650" width="865" aria-labelledby="fig13a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span> Recurrent primary sclerosing cholangitis. <b>(a)</b> Thick-section <abbr title="MR cholangiopancreatography">MRCP</abbr> image shows multifocal areas of ductal irregularity and strictures (arrow), a finding that reflects recurrent primary sclerosing cholangitis after liver transplantation. A right breast implant (*) is also incidentally seen. <b>(b)</b> Percutaneous cholangiogram helps confirm the presence of ductal irregularity (arrow). * = breast implant.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130023&amp;id=fig13a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130023/asset/images/large/rg.351130023.fig13b.jpeg" height="650" width="810" aria-labelledby="fig13b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span> Recurrent primary sclerosing cholangitis. <b>(a)</b> Thick-section <abbr title="MR cholangiopancreatography">MRCP</abbr> image shows multifocal areas of ductal irregularity and strictures (arrow), a finding that reflects recurrent primary sclerosing cholangitis after liver transplantation. A right breast implant (*) is also incidentally seen. <b>(b)</b> Percutaneous cholangiogram helps confirm the presence of ductal irregularity (arrow). * = breast implant.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130023&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130023/asset/images/large/rg.351130023.fig14a.jpeg" height="671" width="930" aria-labelledby="fig14a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span> Recurrent fibrosis and mesenchymal tumor 10 years after liver transplantation. <b>(a)</b> Unenhanced T1-weighted MR image shows a small liver with a 4-cm well-circumscribed left hepatic lobe lesion (black arrow) and marked volume loss (white arrow) along the periphery of the right hepatic lobe. <b>(b)</b> T2-weighted MR image shows hyperintensity in the mass (black arrow) and in the region of volume loss (white arrow). <b>(c)</b> MR image obtained in the arterial phase shows hyperenhancement (black arrow) in the mass but not along the periphery of the right hepatic lobe (white arrow). <b>(d)</b> MR image obtained 3 minutes after administration of contrast material shows that the tumor is relatively hyperenhancing (black arrow) relative to adjacent liver. Delayed hyperenhancement is also seen with linear margins (white arrow), a finding that indicates fibrosis in the right hepatic lobe. Histologic analysis of the left hepatic lobe lesion revealed a mesenchymal tumor.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130023&amp;id=fig14a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130023/asset/images/large/rg.351130023.fig14b.jpeg" height="671" width="946" aria-labelledby="fig14b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14b</span> Recurrent fibrosis and mesenchymal tumor 10 years after liver transplantation. <b>(a)</b> Unenhanced T1-weighted MR image shows a small liver with a 4-cm well-circumscribed left hepatic lobe lesion (black arrow) and marked volume loss (white arrow) along the periphery of the right hepatic lobe. <b>(b)</b> T2-weighted MR image shows hyperintensity in the mass (black arrow) and in the region of volume loss (white arrow). <b>(c)</b> MR image obtained in the arterial phase shows hyperenhancement (black arrow) in the mass but not along the periphery of the right hepatic lobe (white arrow). <b>(d)</b> MR image obtained 3 minutes after administration of contrast material shows that the tumor is relatively hyperenhancing (black arrow) relative to adjacent liver. Delayed hyperenhancement is also seen with linear margins (white arrow), a finding that indicates fibrosis in the right hepatic lobe. Histologic analysis of the left hepatic lobe lesion revealed a mesenchymal tumor.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130023&amp;id=fig14b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130023/asset/images/large/rg.351130023.fig14c.jpeg" height="656" width="935" aria-labelledby="fig14c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14c</span> Recurrent fibrosis and mesenchymal tumor 10 years after liver transplantation. <b>(a)</b> Unenhanced T1-weighted MR image shows a small liver with a 4-cm well-circumscribed left hepatic lobe lesion (black arrow) and marked volume loss (white arrow) along the periphery of the right hepatic lobe. <b>(b)</b> T2-weighted MR image shows hyperintensity in the mass (black arrow) and in the region of volume loss (white arrow). <b>(c)</b> MR image obtained in the arterial phase shows hyperenhancement (black arrow) in the mass but not along the periphery of the right hepatic lobe (white arrow). <b>(d)</b> MR image obtained 3 minutes after administration of contrast material shows that the tumor is relatively hyperenhancing (black arrow) relative to adjacent liver. Delayed hyperenhancement is also seen with linear margins (white arrow), a finding that indicates fibrosis in the right hepatic lobe. Histologic analysis of the left hepatic lobe lesion revealed a mesenchymal tumor.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130023&amp;id=fig14c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130023/asset/images/large/rg.351130023.fig14d.jpeg" height="656" width="940" aria-labelledby="fig14d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14d</span> Recurrent fibrosis and mesenchymal tumor 10 years after liver transplantation. <b>(a)</b> Unenhanced T1-weighted MR image shows a small liver with a 4-cm well-circumscribed left hepatic lobe lesion (black arrow) and marked volume loss (white arrow) along the periphery of the right hepatic lobe. <b>(b)</b> T2-weighted MR image shows hyperintensity in the mass (black arrow) and in the region of volume loss (white arrow). <b>(c)</b> MR image obtained in the arterial phase shows hyperenhancement (black arrow) in the mass but not along the periphery of the right hepatic lobe (white arrow). <b>(d)</b> MR image obtained 3 minutes after administration of contrast material shows that the tumor is relatively hyperenhancing (black arrow) relative to adjacent liver. Delayed hyperenhancement is also seen with linear margins (white arrow), a finding that indicates fibrosis in the right hepatic lobe. Histologic analysis of the left hepatic lobe lesion revealed a mesenchymal tumor.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130023&amp;id=fig14d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130023/asset/images/large/rg.351130023.fig15a.jpeg" height="899" width="650" aria-labelledby="fig15a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15a</span> PTLD. <b>(a)</b> Unenhanced coronal T1-weighted MR image shows innumerable hypointense hepatic lesions. <b>(b)</b> Coronal T2-weighted MR image shows corresponding areas of hyperintensity. <b>(c)</b> Coronal positron emission tomographic (PET) image shows corresponding hypermetabolic activity (arrows) within the liver and within multiple lymph nodes in the neck, chest, abdomen, pelvis, and extremities.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130023&amp;id=fig15a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130023/asset/images/large/rg.351130023.fig15b.jpeg" height="900" width="585" aria-labelledby="fig15b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15b</span> PTLD. <b>(a)</b> Unenhanced coronal T1-weighted MR image shows innumerable hypointense hepatic lesions. <b>(b)</b> Coronal T2-weighted MR image shows corresponding areas of hyperintensity. <b>(c)</b> Coronal positron emission tomographic (PET) image shows corresponding hypermetabolic activity (arrows) within the liver and within multiple lymph nodes in the neck, chest, abdomen, pelvis, and extremities.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130023&amp;id=fig15b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130023/asset/images/large/rg.351130023.fig15c.jpeg" height="900" width="614" aria-labelledby="fig15c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15c</span> PTLD. <b>(a)</b> Unenhanced coronal T1-weighted MR image shows innumerable hypointense hepatic lesions. <b>(b)</b> Coronal T2-weighted MR image shows corresponding areas of hyperintensity. <b>(c)</b> Coronal positron emission tomographic (PET) image shows corresponding hypermetabolic activity (arrows) within the liver and within multiple lymph nodes in the neck, chest, abdomen, pelvis, and extremities.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130023&amp;id=fig15c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130023/asset/images/large/rg.351130023.fig16a.jpeg" height="620" width="940" aria-labelledby="fig16a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16a</span> Hepatic angiosarcoma. <b>(a)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image shows multiple intrahepatic masses (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image obtained in the portal venous phase shows heterogeneous peripheral and central enhancement (arrows). <b>(c)</b> Contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image obtained in the delayed phase shows progressive centripetal central enhancement (arrows). Percutaneous biopsy revealed hepatic angiosarcoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130023&amp;id=fig16a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130023/asset/images/large/rg.351130023.fig16b.jpeg" height="620" width="935" aria-labelledby="fig16b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16b</span> Hepatic angiosarcoma. <b>(a)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image shows multiple intrahepatic masses (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image obtained in the portal venous phase shows heterogeneous peripheral and central enhancement (arrows). <b>(c)</b> Contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image obtained in the delayed phase shows progressive centripetal central enhancement (arrows). Percutaneous biopsy revealed hepatic angiosarcoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130023&amp;id=fig16b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130023/asset/images/large/rg.351130023.fig16c.jpeg" height="636" width="938" aria-labelledby="fig16c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16c</span> Hepatic angiosarcoma. <b>(a)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image shows multiple intrahepatic masses (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image obtained in the portal venous phase shows heterogeneous peripheral and central enhancement (arrows). <b>(c)</b> Contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image obtained in the delayed phase shows progressive centripetal central enhancement (arrows). Percutaneous biopsy revealed hepatic angiosarcoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130023&amp;id=fig16c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130023/asset/images/large/rg.351130023.fig17.jpeg" height="646" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig17" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17</span> <i>Aspergillus</i> pneumonia. CT image shows several large pulmonary nodules, at least one of which has surrounding ground-glass attenuation (arrow), a finding referred to as the halo sign.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130023&amp;id=fig17">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130023/asset/images/large/rg.351130023.fig18a.jpeg" height="666" width="863" aria-labelledby="fig18a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18a</span> Abscesses secondary to biliary stricture. <b>(a)</b> Thick-section <abbr title="MR cholangiopancreatography">MRCP</abbr> image shows a stricture at the biliary anastomosis site (arrow) with moderate upstream intrahepatic biliary ductal dilatation. The presence of hypointense material on T2-weighted MR images indicates debris within the biliary system just proximal to the stricture. <b>(b)</b> T2-weighted MR image obtained 10 months later, when the patient presented with unintentional weight loss, night sweats, and fatigue, shows several ill-defined round areas of hyperintensity (white arrows), a finding indicative of abscesses, and tubular areas of hyperintensity (black arrows), a finding indicative of intrahepatic ductal dilatation. <b>(c)</b> Contrast-enhanced MR image shows round central areas of hypoenhancement (white arrows), a finding that reflects the liquefied portions of abscesses, and linear areas of hypoenhancement (black arrow), which reflect ductal dilatation. Liver biopsy revealed abscesses.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130023&amp;id=fig18a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130023/asset/images/large/rg.351130023.fig18b.jpeg" height="667" width="812" aria-labelledby="fig18b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18b</span> Abscesses secondary to biliary stricture. <b>(a)</b> Thick-section <abbr title="MR cholangiopancreatography">MRCP</abbr> image shows a stricture at the biliary anastomosis site (arrow) with moderate upstream intrahepatic biliary ductal dilatation. The presence of hypointense material on T2-weighted MR images indicates debris within the biliary system just proximal to the stricture. <b>(b)</b> T2-weighted MR image obtained 10 months later, when the patient presented with unintentional weight loss, night sweats, and fatigue, shows several ill-defined round areas of hyperintensity (white arrows), a finding indicative of abscesses, and tubular areas of hyperintensity (black arrows), a finding indicative of intrahepatic ductal dilatation. <b>(c)</b> Contrast-enhanced MR image shows round central areas of hypoenhancement (white arrows), a finding that reflects the liquefied portions of abscesses, and linear areas of hypoenhancement (black arrow), which reflect ductal dilatation. Liver biopsy revealed abscesses.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130023&amp;id=fig18b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130023/asset/images/large/rg.351130023.fig18c.jpeg" height="603" width="850" aria-labelledby="fig18c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18c</span> Abscesses secondary to biliary stricture. <b>(a)</b> Thick-section <abbr title="MR cholangiopancreatography">MRCP</abbr> image shows a stricture at the biliary anastomosis site (arrow) with moderate upstream intrahepatic biliary ductal dilatation. The presence of hypointense material on T2-weighted MR images indicates debris within the biliary system just proximal to the stricture. <b>(b)</b> T2-weighted MR image obtained 10 months later, when the patient presented with unintentional weight loss, night sweats, and fatigue, shows several ill-defined round areas of hyperintensity (white arrows), a finding indicative of abscesses, and tubular areas of hyperintensity (black arrows), a finding indicative of intrahepatic ductal dilatation. <b>(c)</b> Contrast-enhanced MR image shows round central areas of hypoenhancement (white arrows), a finding that reflects the liquefied portions of abscesses, and linear areas of hypoenhancement (black arrow), which reflect ductal dilatation. Liver biopsy revealed abscesses.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130023&amp;id=fig18c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130023/asset/images/large/rg.351130023.fig19a.jpeg" height="619" width="836" aria-labelledby="fig19a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19a</span> Hematoma after liver transplantation. <b>(a)</b> Longitudinal US image shows hypoechoic material with internal septations (white arrow) interposed between the liver <i>(L)</i> and the diaphragm (black arrow) and extending posteriorly along the liver. <b>(b)</b> T1-weighted MR image shows a corresponding area of hyperintensity (arrow) posterior to the liver <i>(L)</i>. * = susceptibility artifact from spinal hardware.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130023&amp;id=fig19a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.351130023/asset/images/large/rg.351130023.fig19b.jpeg" height="619" width="840" aria-labelledby="fig19b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19b</span> Hematoma after liver transplantation. <b>(a)</b> Longitudinal US image shows hypoechoic material with internal septations (white arrow) interposed between the liver <i>(L)</i> and the diaphragm (black arrow) and extending posteriorly along the liver. <b>(b)</b> T1-weighted MR image shows a corresponding area of hyperintensity (arrow) posterior to the liver <i>(L)</i>. * = susceptibility artifact from spinal hardware.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.351130023&amp;id=fig19b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Starzl TE, Marchioro TL, Vonkaulla KN, Hermann G, Brittain RS, Waddell WR. Homotransplantation of the liver in humans. <em>Surg Gynecol Obstet</em> 1963;117:659–676.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/14100514/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Homotransplantation+of+the+liver+in+humans&amp;author=TE+Starzl&amp;author=TL+Marchioro&amp;author=KN+Vonkaulla&amp;author=G+Hermann&amp;author=RS+Brittain&amp;author=WR+Waddell&amp;publication_year=1963&amp;journal=Surg+Gynecol+Obstet&amp;pages=659-676&amp;pmid=14100514">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="r2" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Dienstag JL, Cosimi AB. Liver transplantation: a vision realized. <em>N Engl J Med</em> 2012;367(16):1483–1485.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1056/NEJMp1210159">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22992048/">PubMed</a></